##Towards the epicentre of a new pneumonia pandemic, how far is the EU from recession?

Contributing Writer | Qian Boyan



The European Union's central government, which has long suffered from weak growth in the euro zone and a lack of strong administrative capacity, now faces a serious outbreak that requires extraordinary means.





The European Union's central government, which has long suffered from weak growth in the euro zone and a lack of strong administrative capacity, now faces a serious outbreak that requires extraordinary means.



Europe is already the most severely affected region in the world with more confirmed cases and deaths than the rest of the world combined. According to the World Health Organization, "Europe has become the epicentre of the new coronavirus pandemic. ".

In addition to putting pressure on the health sector, the full impact of the epidemic on European society is gradually being felt as countries step up their epidemic prevention measures, whether in the service sector, the real economy or the financial sector.

The question is simply whether the European Union, which has been sluggish for years, will be pushed into recession by the epidemic, compared with China, which still manages to grow by about 6% a year?

Clearing-house industry

Unlike other metro lines in Italy, which are old and unsanitary, the Milan Metro Line 5, which opened in 2013, is clean and tidy. The route, known locally as the purple line, stretches West to the outskirts of the city, and its normally sparsely populated terminus has been lavishly restored. This is Stadio Giuseppe Meazza meacha stadium.

At 8 pm on 12 March, the MEACHA stadium was supposed to be packed with people, and it was supposed to be the quarter-finals of the Europa League between Inter Milan and Getafe. The fact of the matter is, there was no one on or off the field.

"Even if we lose the game, we will not go to Milan. The health of the players is more important than anything. I will not let them risk going to Italy, " said Getafe President Angel Torres on March 10.

What happened to Inter is happening to all the Italian teams and will happen to all the European teams very soon.

On March 4, when Italy had 3,100 confirmed cases of the new crown, Prime Minister Contes announced on the night that all sports must be empty until April 3, among them was the Serie A showdown on March 8th, as CLUBE ATLTICO Juventus took on Inter Milan in the Inter Derby.

As in Europe's five major leagues in the business operation of the relatively poor, the most money-strapped Serie A, an open game means that the loss of a great deal more. CLUBE ATLTICO Juventus and Inter alone will lose at least $6.6 m on the basis of last year's box office receipts. A month on the pitch means a loss of $29m, based on UEFA's reported earnings of $276m from last season's Serie A tickets.

The only good news is that the empty field does not affect the team's broadcast revenue. The average Serie A team's broadcast revenues are about three times those from tickets, and the 20 teams'total broadcast revenues last season amounted to $1.15 bn, which should have been the club's last resort. But with the outbreak of the disease in Italy, March 10, the empty field game finally became a complete shutdown of all games. It also means that a month of losses in Serie A could swell to at least $150m -- a figure that does not take into account the more lucrative Champions League, and few believe Italy will be able to contain the outbreak by April 3rd.

Italy is just the tip of the iceberg.

On March 10, the same day that Contes announced a month long lockout in Serie A, Paris and Madrid simultaneously announced that France and La Liga would also be open for at least a month. As for the Bundesliga, which has the highest attendance, Bayern Munich and Borussia Dortmund's Bavaria and North Rhine Westphalia have announced the suspension of all activities involving more than 1,000 people, including Dortmund's game against Schalke on Saturday, Revierderby will also have to play in the open. On March 13th the DFB also announced that the Bundesliga would be suspended until April 20th. So far, only the Premier League has not issued a vacancy order in the big five. However, the FA is expected to issue a vacancy order next week, according to the Sun.

If all five leagues were eventually shut down, all clubs would lose more than $1.5 billion a month. According to l'equipe, UEFA will announce next Tuesday that the euro 2016 tournament will be postponed to 2021, which would mean a loss of at least 1.6 billion euros for the host country.

The ban on activity by more than, people also touches the Convention and exhibition industry.

"This is a major blow, so there will be no refund for exhibitors, " Said Olive Ris, who is also a member of the International Trade Association. Ris, Chief Executive of the Geneva Motor Show, the Swiss government on February 28th lifted a ban on the 90th Geneva Motor Show. 600,000 visitors and more than 15,000 professionals and media personnel were supposed to bring in between SFR20M and SFR25M to exhibitors and local catering and accommodation businesses.

Not Just Geneva Motor Show, but in less than a month, a number of well-known European fairs, including the Hanover Industrial Fair, the Leipzig Book Fair, the Venice Fiesta and the Mobile World Congress in Barcelona, have been cancelled or significantly postponed. The Mobile World Congress and the Hanover Industry Fair, which represent the top events in the technology and industry sectors, respectively brought about 460 million revenue and more than 200,000 visitors to the region.

Unlike empty-field Games, the sports industry can still rely on broadcast fees, and shows that emphasize interaction and commerce have little chance of moving online. In Germany alone, cancellations through March 9 will cost 890 million euros in direct losses, according to estimates by the German Association of Trade Fairs, if you include transport companies, exhibition operations, equipment rental and trade companies, including a number of exhibition service companies, indirect losses of about 2.13 billion euros.

In contrast to the big-name Convention and exhibition organizers, the Convention and Exhibition Service Companies that rely on the convention itself are mostly small and micro enterprises with fewer than 50 employees, and 80% of these companies'expenses during the preparation period of the exhibition depend on the refund of the exhibitors. But as with the Geneva Motor Show, to ensure their public reputation, organizers often return only the cost of admission to visitors, and the costs paid by exhibitors are not or are only partially refundable. As a result, the exhibition service companies at the bottom of the food chain will soon face huge cash flow pressure.

The German Finance Ministry said it was getting calls from more than 100 convention and Exhibition Services Companies asking for bail-outs every day, with about 250 small and micro businesses about to be cut off from their funding.

On March 11th KAI Hattendorf, chairman of the World Association of Convention and Exhibition Industries, said the new coronavirus had cost the industry at least $14 billion globally, most of it in Europe, where the disease is most severe.

Frozen liquid industry

Alitalia is perhaps the most apt description of a bankruptcy specialist.

In the 2008 financial crisis, Alitalia went bankrupt. But with the financial backing of Berlusconi, then Italy's prime minister, Alitalia continued to struggle. In 2014 Alitalia was finally bought by the Middle Eastern tycoons Etihad Airways, but after three years of losses Alitalia, which was abandoned by Etihad, went bankrupt in 2017. Then the Italian government, which rushed to buy its stake, was locked in. Until the start of the year, Alitalia, which received another $400m in loans, had a silver lining: revenue in January rose 3% to 4% from a year earlier, the best figure in years.

Now, that hope is gone.

Although the Italian government has not ordered a ban on all international flights, but as of the 13th, France, Austria, Spain and other countries have suspended all flights to Italy, it is an indisputable fact that travel demand has been greatly reduced under the impact of the epidemic. Passenger traffic at Italy's major airports, including those in Milan, Venice and Genoa, shrank by more than 40 percent before Contes announced a blockade of the northern regions, according to IlSole24ore, an Italian aviation application. Alitalia, which has just started to improve, has cancelled 38 flights and, according to Corriere della Sera, has changed its 4,000-person contract to a seven-month short-term one.

Not only was Italia already weak, but Lufthansa, Europe's largest airline, was not immune.

As of March 12, Lufthansa had announced the cancellation of more than 7,100 flights in March, equivalent to about 25 percent of its capacity. That figure is expected to rise to 50% in the next week, according to Carsten Spohr, Lufthansa's CEO  , all of the company's A380s had to stay in the hangar: "Our primary objective is to reduce losses and ensure the company's liquidity. "

The bad news just keeps on coming.

"A large number of new US clusters [ of virus infections ] have been spread by European travellers" , said Donald Trump, which imposed a 30-day travel ban on Schengen Area across the Pacific Ocean on March 12. For Lufthansa, which shares flights with Transatlantic flight and has a 36 per cent market share, the ban is tantamount to A Bolt from the Blue. Lufthansa shares fell as much as 13 per cent during the day and are down nearly 50 per cent since the start of the year.

Air france-klm, the EU's second-largest carrier, is no better. As early as February, air france-klm reported a 24.7 percent decline in passenger traffic in the Asian region. In March, when the base camp burned, Air France KLM announced it had canceled more than 25 percent of its flights in Europe, and more than 50 percent of its flights to Italy were canceled. Air France KLM, which works with Delta, is also the second largest provider of air travel, with 29 percent of its shares listed on the Transatlantic flight. Air France KLM shares also fell more than 10 percent on the 12th.

European aviation industry has always been due to over-protection of national governments, small countries and other factors show a low degree of integration, fragmentation of the obvious characteristics, Lufthansa in the European market share is only about 6% . The spread of the main market and the low risk of small size make European airlines the biggest losers from the epidemic.

On March 5th Britain's budget airline, Freiby, became the first airline to be hit by the outbreak. In a financial forecast released on the same day by IATA, the International Air Transport Association estimated that the outbreak would cost airlines $43.9 billion in Europe and $21.1 billion in North America.

But the outbreak may yet spur a wave of consolidation and restructuring in Europe, with smaller carriers struggling to cope with international competition.

Bigger and more far-reaching than the civil aviation industry is tourism.

Italy is the world's largest holder of cultural heritage alongside China, with tourism accounting for 12% of GDP and a total output of 230 billion euros. A one-month shutdown of Italy's tourism industry is equivalent to a loss of 20 billion euros. And unlike the rest of the world, where winter is a low season for tourism, February-march is the hottest ski season in northern Italy, where the outbreak is most severe. In the South Tyrol Autonomous Province, the cost of a single night at a ski villa can reach as much as 1,700 euros in January, according to interface news.

Fabio Primerano, president of the Italian Tourism Association, estimates that the cancellation rate for hotels across Italy has now reached more than 80% , with the remainder mainly for foreign visitors'summer travel plans if the epidemic is not contained by then, that part of the order will eventually disappear, too.

The shrinking tourism market is most evident in Austria, Italy's northern neighbour. As of March 13, Austria has announced the closure of all ski resorts in the country. Last year, 2.9 million tourists from Italy booked accommodation in Austria, up from 837,000 this year, according to figures compiled by the Austrian Hotel Association's President, Michaela Reitterer, who spoke to the standard In Mozart's native Salzburg, the average tour guide used to receive 40 Italian groups in March, up from less than one this year.

In fact, as early as February, the European tourism market has been feeling the chill brought by the epidemic. According to an analysis in early March by Tourism Economics, a consultancy, the outbreak caused at least 7m Chinese tourists to abandon plans to travel to Europe and hurt the local Tourism industry by 17 to 25 per cent.

For local groups dependent on Chinese tourists, the surge in China and Europe has meant a collapse in business for at least a quarter. With 10 to 15 orders a month in previous years, Flyingphoto, a munich-based wedding photography service for Chinese, now relies on a sporadic business of local students getting married. The firm usually charges around $1,500 a day for each order, covering the whole of Europe. Now, to ensure that the money chain does not break, the company has started to engage in Daigou services.

The real economy faces recession

There were no stoppages, no shutdowns, but that doesn't mean Europe's real economy is immune.

"German industry is facing the longest recession since reunification, with six consecutive quarters of declining industrial output, " read a widely circulated letter from the Bdi Industry Association to the Federal Government on March 12.

- 5% , the latest forecast by the German Industry Association for the growth rate of industrial output in the EU's largest industrial country this year, has doubled from the-2% forecast at the beginning of the year.

As a technology industry is not developed continent, the traditional industries and high-end manufacturing industry has always been Europe's fist industry. But compared with parts of the service industry that are already in tatters, europe's real economy remains stable in the short term, driven by political headwinds, global demand and inventory overhang along long supply chains. But in the medium to long term, supply chain problems and falling aggregate demand caused by the outbreak will hit the real economy hard at the production and consumption ends.

This is particularly true in supply chains where inventory shortages are imminent.

Most of China's provinces have experienced extensive work stoppages since February. As the factory of the world and a shipping power with nearly all of the world's top ten ports, China has a profound influence on the EU's manufacturing industry in raw materials and primary processed goods. The impact of China's massive work stoppage has yet to be felt in Europe, thanks to a buffer of about six weeks by sea and three weeks by road between China and Europe.

But as the cushion wears off, European industry is already feeling the chill. Frankfurt's airport and China's cargo volumes fell 8% in March from a year earlier.

The car industry is the most important industry in the secondary sector of the economy, providing more than 13.8 million jobs and contributing 7 percent of the EU's gross domestic product, and about 10 percent in Italy.

Volkmar Denner, CEO  of Bosch, the world's largest auto parts maker, has previously said that "the COVID-19 epidemic could affect the global automotive supply chain that is heavily dependent on China" , previously infected by the Chinese employees of the Weibaster Company in Wuhan also has the group's largest worldwide production base of car skylights. Moreover, the European car industry, which is undergoing an electrification transition, is more than 90 per cent dependent on Asian manufacturers for its power batteries.

The supply chain problems caused by China's outbreak are just the first domino to fall. With Italy out of control, even the European Union's car supply chain has been in trouble.

From Milan to Turin, Polesine has long been a base for Italian industry and the car industry, as well as an important link in the supply chain of the European car industry around Germany. On March 11, WHO director-general Tan Desai announced that the new coronavirus had become a "global pandemic" , italian manufacturers such as Fiat Chrysler, tire maker Pirelli and brake maker Braeber have announced plans to close some local factories and reduce production.

The new cases have been confirmed by staff at PSA's Moorhouse Plant in France, BMW's Munich R & D Headquarters, Daimler's lassiter plant and ODEINGERSTADT headquarters. According to the author from the Internal E-mail of major enterprises, although the government has not issued mandatory measures to stop work, but the major companies have mobilized employees to work from home. As the French government and most of the German states in the 13th has announced that next Monday school closed, substantial large-scale shutdown has been inevitable.

On the consumer side, the impact of the outbreak on Europe's car industry was already apparent in February. Global sales fell 25 per cent in February from a year earlier. Excluding China, where national sales plunged 80 per cent in February, Europe, where sales fell 3.5 per cent, was far worse than the 8 per cent and 14 per cent growth seen in North America and Latin America. As for the local epidemic out of control in March, no authority has yet made a sales forecast. But UNRAE, the Italian Motor Trade Association, expects Italian car sales to shrink by at least 15% in 2020, equivalent to an economic loss of $29 billion.

The lackluster progress of the auto industry is just the tip of the iceberg of the impact of the epidemic on the real economy.

A survey of 577 companies doing business with China by the European Trade Association found that 80 percent said orders had fallen sharply, with only 6.8 percent reporting an increase, mostly medical supply companies.

BASF group, the world's largest chemicals company, warned in late February of a tight supply chain in Europe's other strong industrial chemical industry and declined to give a forecast for this year's performance. In March, the Lombardy-based IGM company, the world's largest maker of photoinitiators, announced it was shutting down production.

In the aerospace industry, Airbus, which made a name for itself last year with its new A321XLR and its old rival Boeing in the 737Max crisis, is no exception. Compared with 200 orders secured in January, Airbus added an embarrassing zero in February. Airasia's long-distance announcement of a delay in its A330neo order forced Airbus to cut production of the aircraft.

In the energy sector, the slump in demand caused by the outbreak within a week and tensions between Saudi Arabia and Russia have triggered a collapse in oil prices. The European Union (including Britain) , home to Royal Dutch Shell, BP and total, has directly created 70,000 jobs and more than 50 billion euros in output. While the big three have yet to make a formal statement about the epidemic and the oil price crisis, the experience of 2016, when oil prices fell to $50 a barrel, suggests that a sharp decline in performance and large-scale layoffs are inevitable. Between 2015 and 2016, royal shell cut 10,000 jobs, total cut more than 2,000 and BP cut 4,000.

Even relatively isolated nuclear plants have been affected by the outbreak. EDF, the world's largest nuclear power operator, confirmed at the end of February that it had confirmed staff with CGNPC at its Hinkley Point C nuclear plant construction project in the UK, leading to the isolation of its local office, in early March, three more workers at three of France's own nuclear plants have been diagnosed. EDF assured Maqueron on March 13th that it could keep France's electricity supply stable for more than three months with a 40% absence rate.

During the bailout,

March 12 was perhaps the darkest day in the 21st century for European stock markets.

The DAX index in Frankfurt fell 12.3% , the CAC 40 in Paris fell 12.2% , the FTSE 100 in London fell 10.9% , the SMI in Switzerland fell 9.7% and Italy's 40 index fell 16.6% . In a single day, trillion euros of market value has evaporated.

The main reason for the sharp fall in major European stock indexes was the European Central Bank's refusal to cut eurozone deposit rates further that day.

Compared with the Federal Reserve and the Bank of England, which have already announced emergency interest rate cuts, the euro zone's current 0.5% deposit rate has left European banks far behind their U.S. and Asian peers in profitability. Low interest rates also leave the ECB with little room for manoeuvre.

On the 12th, as the European Central Bank confirmed that it would keep key euro zone interest rates unchanged, it also announced that it would inject extra liquidity into the economy by expanding quantitative easing and easing banking regulation. Specific proposals include more temporary long-term refinancing operations (LTRO) for banks, more favourable terms for temporary long-term refinancing operations to be carried out over the next year, additional purchases of $120bn of assets focused on private sector bonds by the end of the year, and a postponement of this year's bank stress tests.

The ECB currently buys about $20bn of bonds a month, of which only $5bn is corporate debt and the rest is mostly eurozone government debt.

Andrea Enria, head of the European Banking Regulatory Commission, also said the aim of the partial deregulation was to make banks focus on lending to small and micro businesses and private households: "banks need to continue to provide capital to cash-strapped households and businesses. "

Three days ago, the European Central Bank headquarters in Frankfurt confirmed a new coronary case. A number of eurozone central bankers, including the governor of the Bank of Italy, also opted for a video link during their meeting on December 12th.

Fiscal Stimulus by European governments is the key to stabilising the economy, compared with the ECB's monetary stimulus, which has few bullets to fire and interest rates to fall. European countries experienced the European debt crisis, the implementation of fiscal discipline, the debt ratio has improved significantly. In contrast to the highly indebted US or Japan, European Finance Ministries still have the strength to deal with the impact of the epidemic.

European countries are indeed moving.

"No one is going to lose their jobs because of this outbreak! " Italy's finance minister, Gualtieri, officially announced a $25 billion fiscal stimulus to the health care system and economy on Monday, equivalent to 1.1% of Italy's GDP.

"twenty-five billion euros is to prepare everyone, whether it's the health care system or the economy, to deal with the difficulties, " he said, contes and the Gualtieri were in Rome that day to detail the package, which will take effect on the 13th: The first $12 billion will go directly to the health care system and to businesses and families.

The Italian government has allowed temporary collection of pension and social security contributions for employees, tax breaks for businesses, and unemployment benefits for self-employed workers. So far 7.5 billion euros have been distributed to businesses and households affected by the outbreak.

Earlier, on March 5th, Contes had planned a $75bn fiscal stimulus, but that was unrealistic for a heavily indebted country with a zero growth economy. The move would add at least $20bn to the debt of Italy, Europe's second-largest debtor after Greece. Italian government bond prices have risen 100 basis points. Even the current $25bn bail-out will require EU funding.

French President Maqueron also announced in his speech on the 12th that businesses in France can defer payment of income taxes and social security contributions, and that the BPI, the country's investment bank, will provide guarantees and bridge loans, the government will also pay part of the wages and subsidies for home-based workers. The French Finance Ministry and LYSE PALACE WILL CO-ORDINATE IF companies run into problems with international customers because of supply chain disruptions or capacity constraints.

"We put all our weapons on the table, " Olaf Scholz, Germany's Chancellor of the Exchequer, announced in Berlin on Wednesday, compared with France's failure to agree on a specific amount for its fiscal stimulus, the federal government, through the German bank KFW, will guarantee up to $460bn. "another $93bn if necessary. This is just the beginning. We don't have a CAP. "

The German government and the bureau of Labour also provided short-term payments to businesses and allowed them to defer their taxes. Short-term pay refers to the period during which the state will bear the wages of employees in case the enterprise is shut down due to an epidemic or force majeure, in order to avoid redundancy.

At the EU level, EU CORONA FONDS, a $25 billion funding facility for health care and small and medium enterprises, was also announced on November 11th by the commission's President, jean-claude von Der Laing, it also does not rule out using the fund as part of an aid package for Italy.

However, the $25bn stimulus package from the European Commission, the EU's "central government" , is equivalent to just 0.25 per cent of eurozone GDP. Even the British, who have been reluctant to suspend Premier League matches due to too few tests, announced a # 30bn package on Sunday, it even includes generous measures such as a # 3,000 cash grant to each SME and a one-year exemption from sales tax for the catering and tourism sectors. By contrast, the commission appears to lack the boldness of the Chancellor of the Exchequer to "do whatever it takes" .

The ECB cut its 2020 and 2021 growth forecasts for the eurozone to 0.3% to 0.8% and 1.3% on the 12th. Previous forecasts were 1.2 per cent and 1.4 per cent, respectively.

But can the European Union deliver a satisfactory response to a serious outbreak requiring extraordinary means in the long-term growth-weary eurozone countries and in the absence of a strong administration?
